</ul>
<p><a name="Footnotes" id="Footnotes"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Memetics&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Footnotes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Footnotes</span></h3>
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://jom-emit.cfpm.org/" class="external text" title="http://jom-emit.cfpm.org/" rel="nofollow">Journal of Memetics - Aims and Scope</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> Benitez-Bribiesca, Luis (2001): <i><a href="http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/339/33905206.pdf" class="external text" title="http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/339/33905206.pdf" rel="nofollow">Memetics: A dangerous idea</a></i>. Interciecia 26: 29–31, p.&#160;29.</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Terrence_Deacon" title="Terrence Deacon">Terrence Deacon</a>, The trouble with memes (and what to do about it). <i>The Semiotic Review of Books</i> 10(3).</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Kalevi_Kull" title="Kalevi Kull">Kalevi Kull</a> (2000), Copy versus translate, meme versus sign: development of biological textuality. <i>European Journal for Semiotic Studies</i> 12(1), 101–120.</li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://human-nature.com/nibbs/02/cults.html" class="external text" title="http://human-nature.com/nibbs/02/cults.html" rel="nofollow">Sex, Drugs, and Cults by H. Keith Henson</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.mankindquarterly.org/summer2006_henson.html" class="external text" title="http://www.mankindquarterly.org/summer2006_henson.html" rel="nofollow">Evolutionary Psychology, Memes and the Origin of War</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.kuro5hin.org/story/2006/4/17/194059/296/" class="external text" title="http://www.kuro5hin.org/story/2006/4/17/194059/296/" rel="nofollow">Evolutionary Psychology, Memes and the Origin of War || kuro5hin.org</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/eserv.php?pid=UQ:8801&amp;dsID=sjw_ijpm_05.pdf" class="external text" title="http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/eserv.php?pid=UQ:8801&amp;dsID=sjw_ijpm_05.pdf" rel="nofollow">A Memetic Paradigm of Project Management</a> (International Journal of Project Management, 23 (8) 575-583)</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> “The Evolution of IT Innovations in Swedish Organizations: A Darwinian Critique of ‘Lamarckian’ Institutional Economics”, <b>Journal of Evolutionary Economics</b>, vol. 17, No. 1 (Feb 2007)</li>
</ol>
